{"questionId":"22954","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><strong>This question explores models for the height of water in a cylindrical container as&nbsp;water drains out.</strong></p>\n<p><br>The diagram shows a cylindrical water container of height <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></math> metres and base radius <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> metre.&nbsp;At the base of the container is a small circular valve, which enables water to drain out.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/64a39ed87d88b5efb29a43bb69e63e116259dc65.png\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">Eva closes the valve and fills the container with water.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">At time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, Eva opens the valve. She records the height, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> metres, of water remaining in&nbsp;the container every <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math> minutes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/4410e75e7a94ef1d782e1ce1b65bc8f0e0368dc2.png\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">Eva first tries to model the height using a linear function, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Eva uses the equation of the regression line of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>, to predict the time it will take for all&nbsp;the water to drain out of the container.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Eva thinks she can improve her model by using a quadratic function, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi></math>,&nbsp;where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Eva uses this equation to predict the time it will take for all the water to drain out of the&nbsp;container and obtains an answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math> minutes.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> be the volume, in cubic metres, of water in the container at time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp;minutes.<br>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math> be the radius, in metres, of the circular valve.</p>\n<p>Eva does some research and discovers a formula for the rate of change of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msqrt><mn>70</mn><mo> </mo><mn>560</mn><mi>h</mi></msqrt></math></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Eva measures the radius of the valve to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>023</mn></math> metres. Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math> be the time, in minutes,&nbsp;it takes for all the water to drain out of the container.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Use the general solution from part (d) and the initial condition <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></math> to predict the&nbsp;value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>⇒</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>17640</mn><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0134687</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>substituting <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and their non-zero value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0134687</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>023</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;(minutes)&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>25</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4606</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22954","referenceCode":"21N.3.AHL.TZ0.2e","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Use the general solution from part (d) and the initial condition h(0)=3.2 to predict the value of T.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"e","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.9—Differentiating standard functions and derivative rules","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.14—Setting up a DE, solve by separating variables","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.16—Eulers method for 1st order DEs","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.13—Non-linear regression"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}